    id: "note_eng_001",
    subject: "English",
    topic: "Grammar",
    title: "Tenses — Complete Guide (All 12 Tenses)",
    content: `TENSES are the backbone of English grammar and one of the most tested areas in CUET. There are 3 time frames (Present, Past, Future) × 4 aspects (Simple, Continuous, Perfect, Perfect Continuous) = 12 tenses total.

━━━ PRESENT TENSES ━━━
• Simple Present: Subject + V1 (he/she/it → V1+s)
  Use: Habit, general truth, newspaper headlines.
  Signal words: always, usually, often, sometimes, every day, never.
  Example: "She reads the newspaper every morning."

• Present Continuous: Subject + is/am/are + V-ing
  Use: Action happening right now, temporary actions, future plans.
  Signal words: now, at the moment, currently, look!, listen!
  Example: "They are preparing for CUET these days."

• Present Perfect: Subject + has/have + V3
  Use: Recent past with present effect, experience, result.
  Signal words: just, already, yet, ever, never, recently, so far, since, for.
  Example: "I have just finished my revision."

• Present Perfect Continuous: Subject + has/have + been + V-ing
  Use: Action started in past, still continuing.
  Signal words: for, since, all day, how long.
  Example: "She has been studying for three hours."

━━━ PAST TENSES ━━━
• Simple Past: Subject + V2
  Use: Completed action at a definite past time.
  Signal words: yesterday, ago, last week/year, in 2020, once, when.
  Example: "He appeared in CUET last year."

• Past Continuous: Subject + was/were + V-ing
  Use: Action in progress at a specific past time; interrupted action.
  Signal words: while, when (background action), at that time, at 5 o'clock yesterday.
  Example: "I was studying when the power went off."

• Past Perfect: Subject + had + V3
  Use: Action completed before another past action (earlier of two past actions).
  Signal words: before, after, by the time, already, when, as soon as, since.
  Example: "She had already left before I arrived." (Leaving happened first.)

• Past Perfect Continuous: Subject + had + been + V-ing
  Use: Action started before a past time and was still going on or just stopped.
  Signal words: for, since (with past reference), before.
  Example: "He had been waiting for two hours when the bus finally arrived."

━━━ FUTURE TENSES ━━━
• Simple Future: Subject + will/shall + V1
  Use: Spontaneous decision, prediction, promise, offer.
  Signal words: tomorrow, next week/month, soon, in the future.
  Example: "I will call you when I reach home."

• Future Continuous: Subject + will + be + V-ing
  Use: Action in progress at a future point in time.
  Signal words: at this time tomorrow, by next Monday.
  Example: "This time next week, I will be sitting in the exam hall."

• Future Perfect: Subject + will + have + V3
  Use: Action that will be completed before a specific future time.
  Signal words: by, by the time, before (with future reference).
  Example: "I will have revised all chapters by Sunday."

• Future Perfect Continuous: Subject + will + have + been + V-ing
  Use: Duration of an action up to a point in the future.
  Signal words: for + duration + by future time.
  Example: "By next year, she will have been teaching for 20 years."

━━━ COMMON MISTAKES ━━━
✗ "I am knowing the answer." → ✓ "I know the answer." (Stative verbs don't use continuous)
✗ "She is having a car." → ✓ "She has a car." (possession = simple)
✗ "I have seen him yesterday." → ✓ "I saw him yesterday." (definite past = simple past)
✗ "When I will reach, I will call." → ✓ "When I reach, I will call." (time clause = present, not future)

Stative verbs (never use in continuous): know, understand, believe, want, need, love, hate, see, hear, smell, taste, have (possession), own, contain.`,
    keyPoints: [
      "12 tenses = 3 time frames × 4 aspects (Simple, Continuous, Perfect, Perfect Continuous)",
      "Signal words: 'just/already/yet' → Present Perfect; 'yesterday/ago' → Simple Past",
      "Past Perfect = 'had + V3' — always describes the EARLIER of two past events",
      "Stative verbs (know, love, want, own) NEVER use continuous forms",
      "Time clauses (when, if, after, before, as soon as) use Present tense for future meaning",
      "For + duration (for 3 hours); Since + starting point (since 2020) — both with Perfect tenses",
      "Future Perfect 'will have + V3' — action complete before a future deadline",
      "Present Continuous can express future plans: 'I am meeting him tomorrow'"
    ],
    tags: ["Grammar", "Tenses", "Verbs", "CUET English", "Foundation"]
