    subject: "English",
    topic: "Vocabulary",
    title: "Idioms and Phrases — 60+ Important with Meanings",
    content: `IDIOMS are fixed expressions whose meaning cannot be understood word by word. CUET includes 3-5 idiom questions. Here are 60+ grouped by theme.

━━━ BODY PARTS IDIOMS ━━━
• Bite the bullet — endure a painful/difficult situation bravely
  "She bit the bullet and went through the surgery."
• Break a leg — good luck (theatrical expression)
• Cost an arm and a leg — very expensive
  "That diamond ring cost an arm and a leg."
• Get cold feet — become nervous/hesitant before doing something
  "He got cold feet before the stage performance."
• Keep an eye on — watch carefully / supervise
  "Please keep an eye on the children."
• On the tip of my tongue — about to remember something
• Pull someone's leg — to tease/joke with someone
• Have a heart of gold — be very kind and generous
• Turn a blind eye — ignore something deliberately
• Lend an ear — to listen attentively
• Keep your chin up — stay positive in a difficult situation
• Get something off your chest — reveal something that's been troubling you

━━━ ANIMAL IDIOMS ━━━
• Let the cat out of the bag — reveal a secret accidentally
  "She let the cat out of the bag about the surprise party."
• Kill two birds with one stone — achieve two goals with one action
• Raining cats and dogs — raining very heavily
• The elephant in the room — obvious problem that no one wants to discuss
• A wolf in sheep's clothing — dangerous person pretending to be harmless
• A dark horse — unknown person who unexpectedly succeeds
• Barking up the wrong tree — accusing/suspecting the wrong person
• Beat a dead horse — waste effort on something hopeless
• Take the bull by the horns — deal with a difficult situation directly
• Fish out of water — person in an unfamiliar/uncomfortable situation

━━━ COLOR IDIOMS ━━━
• Green with envy — very jealous
• Caught red-handed — caught in the act of doing something wrong
• Once in a blue moon — very rarely
• Tickled pink — very pleased/delighted
• Black sheep — the odd one out; person who brings shame to a group
• In the black — making profit (account in surplus)
• In the red — in debt/loss (account in deficit)
• Gray area — situation that is not clearly defined or settled
• Show someone in a good light — make someone appear favorable
• Green light — approval to proceed

━━━ NATURE / WEATHER IDIOMS ━━━
• Every cloud has a silver lining — every bad situation has some good aspect
• Under the weather — feeling ill or unwell
• Steal someone's thunder — take away someone's glory/attention
• A storm in a teacup — a big fuss about something trivial
• Break the ice — initiate conversation in an awkward situation
• In hot water — in trouble
• Come rain or shine — no matter what happens
• On thin ice — in a risky/dangerous situation

━━━ COMMON EVERYDAY IDIOMS ━━━
• Bite off more than you can chew — take on more responsibility than you can handle
• Burn bridges — damage/end relationships permanently
• Hit the nail on the head — describe something exactly right
• Let sleeping dogs lie — avoid bringing up old problems
• Miss the boat — miss an opportunity
• Sit on the fence — avoid taking sides; remain neutral
• Spill the beans — reveal secret information
• The ball is in your court — it's your turn to take action/make a decision
• Under the thumb — completely controlled by someone
• Up in the air — uncertain, not yet decided
• Give someone the cold shoulder — deliberately ignore someone
• Burn the midnight oil — work late into the night
• Hit the sack — go to bed
• A blessing in disguise — something that seems bad but turns out good
• The last straw — the final problem that causes a reaction`,
    keyPoints: [
      "Get cold feet = become nervous/hesitant; Pull someone's leg = tease/joke",
      "Let the cat out of the bag = reveal secret; Kill two birds with one stone = two goals at once",
      "Caught red-handed = caught in the act; Once in a blue moon = very rarely",
      "Under the weather = feeling ill; Burn the midnight oil = work very late",
      "A blessing in disguise = bad thing that turns out good; The last straw = final trigger",
      "Hit the nail on the head = exactly right; Miss the boat = miss an opportunity",
      "Sitting on the fence = not taking sides; Up in the air = uncertain/undecided",
      "Black sheep = family disgrace; Dark horse = unexpected winner"
    ],
    tags: ["Vocabulary", "Idioms", "Phrases", "CUET English", "Expressions"]
