    subject: "English",
    topic: "Grammar",
    title: "English Quick Revision Cheatsheet — CUET Last-Minute Guide",
    content: `This is your complete CUET English revision cheatsheet. Review this the night before the exam.

━━━ TENSE QUICK CHART ━━━
Simple Present: V1 / V1+s — She writes
Present Cont.: is/am/are + V-ing — She is writing
Present Perfect: has/have + V3 — She has written
Present Perf. Cont.: has/have been + V-ing — She has been writing
Simple Past: V2 — She wrote
Past Continuous: was/were + V-ing — She was writing
Past Perfect: had + V3 — She had written
Past Perf. Cont.: had been + V-ing — She had been writing
Simple Future: will/shall + V1 — She will write
Future Cont.: will be + V-ing — She will be writing
Future Perfect: will have + V3 — She will have written
Future Perf. Cont.: will have been + V-ing — She will have been writing

━━━ PASSIVE VOICE QUICK REFERENCE ━━━
is/are + V3 (Simple Present) | was/were + V3 (Simple Past)
is/are being + V3 (Present Cont.) | was/were being + V3 (Past Cont.)
has/have been + V3 (Present Perfect) | had been + V3 (Past Perfect)
will be + V3 (Future) | Modal + be + V3 (Modals)

━━━ NARRATION QUICK RULES ━━━
Simple Present → Simple Past | Present Cont. → Past Cont.
Present Perfect → Past Perfect | Simple Past → Past Perfect
will → would | can → could | may → might | shall → should
Today → that day | Tomorrow → next day | Here → there | This → that

━━━ ARTICLES QUICK RULE ━━━
A/AN: first mention, any one, consonant/vowel sound (NOT spelling)
THE: specific, unique, second mention, superlatives, rivers/oceans/mountain ranges
ZERO: general plurals, uncountable (general), languages, meals, sports, countries (singular)

━━━ COMMON ERROR CHECKLIST ━━━
☐ Subject-verb agreement: Each/everyone → singular; Both/many → plural
☐ Along with/as well as: doesn't change subject number
☐ Either...or / Neither...nor: verb agrees with NEARER subject
☐ Parallel structure: matching grammatical forms in lists
☐ Double negative: "don't know nothing" → "don't know anything"
☐ Dangling modifier: participial phrase must refer to sentence's subject
☐ Pronoun case: between you and ME (not I); It is I (not me) — formal
☐ Reflexive pronoun: myself only when subject = object
☐ Collective nouns: usually singular in CUET
☐ Uncountable nouns: always singular (news, information, luggage)

━━━ MODAL MEANINGS ━━━
Can = ability/informal permission | Could = past ability/polite request
Will = decision/future/promise | Would = polite/conditional/past habit
Shall = formal future/offer | Should = advice/obligation
May = formal permission/possibility | Might = remote possibility
Must = strong necessity/deduction | Need not = no necessity

━━━ VOCABULARY TIPS ━━━
• Words ending in -ous: plentiful, ambiguous, ominous, tenacious, vivacious, voracious
• Words with negative prefix: in- (inept, indifferent), un- (unfathomable), dis- (discrepant), ir- (irrelevant), im- (impetuous), il- (illicit)
• Commonly confused: affect/effect, eminent/imminent, credible/credulous, principal/principle, elicit/illicit, moral/morale
• Top 10 CUET antonyms: Ardent↔Apathetic, Benevolent↔Malevolent, Candid↔Evasive, Diligent↔Indolent, Frugal↔Extravagant, Gallant↔Cowardly, Humble↔Arrogant, Lucid↔Obscure, Reticent↔Talkative, Verbose↔Concise

━━━ FIGURE OF SPEECH IDENTIFIER ━━━
Like/As = SIMILE | A is B = METAPHOR | Non-human does human = PERSONIFICATION
Same start consonant = ALLITERATION | Extreme exaggeration = HYPERBOLE
Word sounds like its meaning = ONOMATOPOEIA | Opposite meaning intended = IRONY
Two contradictory words = OXYMORON | Contradictory but true statement = PARADOX

━━━ COMPREHENSION STRATEGY SUMMARY ━━━
1. Read questions first → Skim passage → Locate → Answer before seeing options → Eliminate
2. Factual: find in text | Inferential: logical deduction | Main idea: covers all | Title: neither too broad nor narrow
3. Vocabulary in context: substitute each option; tone clue: positive/negative
4. WRONG answer traps: extreme language, out of scope, general truth not in passage

━━━ LAST-MINUTE REMINDERS ━━━
• CUET follows British English spelling (colour, behaviour, centre)
• Stative verbs (know, love, want, own, believe) NEVER use continuous forms
• Unless = if not → never say "unless...not"
• Although/though → never add "but" in same sentence
• Because → never add "so" in same sentence
• Time clauses (when, if, after) use Present Tense for future: "When I arrive..." (not "will arrive")`,
